  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Preterm birth continues to be a major public health problem with lasting family and societal
      repercussions. Despite tremendous research effort, prevention strategies have failed, and the
      prevalence of preterm birth in the United States reached 12.3% in 2003.

      Prematurity causes 70% of fetal/neonatal deaths. 11.4% of births are at &lt; 37 weeks'
      gestation. The rate of prematurity increases dramatically with the number of fetuses -
      singletons 10%; twins 54.9%; and triplets 93.6%
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
